##European supermarkets were sold out, even the laundry balls

REPORTER: Editor Lu Yibei: Ya Hanxiang

Hoarding in a crisis is essentially an attempt to control the situation, to feel that at least we are doing something.

“

Hoarding in a crisis is essentially an attempt to control the situation, to feel that at least we are doing something.

”

Supermarkets in Europe have been snapped up by anxious people. At 7 am UK time on March 17, international student Serena Huang went to a TESCO supermarket in Uxbridge, London, to replenish her daily necessities. Although she had just opened the door, she found that eggs, fruit and vegetables, cans and Pasta had been swept away, while the shelves of Toilet Paper and detergent had only a few items left.

Supermarket restocking has completely outpaced the pace of people's buying, and even the racks of laundry balls have been labeled red, with the earliest arrival date being Friday, March 20.

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
The racks of laundry balls are labeled red and the earliest delivery date is Friday, March 20. (photo: Courtesy of Interviewees)

This has been happening in every supermarket in the UK since about two weeks ago. And the rest of Europe also with the spread of the epidemic, a wave of panic buying.

Italy was the first country in Europe to experience an outbreak. Since February 15th, when Italy reported three confirmed cases, panic has spread across the country. Around February 20, social media began to show information about empty supermarkets in northern Italy, the first place in the country to have a confirmed case. Soon, as the epidemic spread across Italy, so did the number of short-selling supermarkets.

Over the next half-month, the buying spread like dominoes across Europe.

Since March, there has been a rapid increase in the number of confirmed cases in European countries, according to the interface news data group, which has collated the cumulative number of newly diagnosed cases in the world's major endemic countries. Panic buying and empty supermarket shelves are popping up in the news.

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
As of March 18, Central Europe time, 191127 cases of COVID-19 pneumonia had been reported globally, including 74,760 in Europe, according to the World Health Organization.

In response to the constant sell-off of supermarkets, almost all European countries have repeatedly stressed to the public that local food and goods are sufficient, really enough to supply everyone's needs.

French economy and Finance Minister Bruno Le Maire and Agriculture and Food Minister Didier Guillaume said at a press conference on March 15 that food and basic necessities would be guaranteed in the coming days and weeks; Germany's Food and agriculture minister, Julia Klokner, also said the same day that there was no shortage of supplies in Germany, where hoarding leads to waste. Panic buying will only put additional pressure on the supply chain, and if everyone is sensible, shelves will be replenished in time.

In Italy and Spain, where the outbreak is most severe, local authorities said there would be no shortage. Italy's agriculture ministry says 740,000 farms, 70,000 food companies and supermarkets are still in operation to ensure supplies.

The Spanish Association for Distributors and Supermarkets, a Spanish Association of Distributors and Supermarkets, says the local logistics system is already robust, with one supermarket per 840 customers in Spain, this means that the nation's superstores are capable of serving every citizen in extreme circumstances.

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
A view from inside Sainsbury's supermarket in London March 18,2010 Source: Interviewees

The truth, however, is that supermarkets have been unable to fill their shelves in the face of panic buying caused by the outbreak.

The reason is simple, first goods from the manufacturer to the warehouse to the store logistics speed, has been unable to keep up with demand.

Ananth Iyer, a professor at the Purdue University, has said that the food supply chain itself does not need to worry, and that modern supermarkets typically store staple products for up to four months to keep the system running. But fresh food doesn't have that cushion. Grocery stores can't store them, and farmers can't make them grow faster. It takes three to four months for an egg to hatch and be eaten. Therefore, too much demand for fresh food may mean that supply will not be able to keep up.

In addition, if the interface news has reported, toilet paper such a large volume of consumer goods, in modern society is also prone to be "robbed of" the situation.

In fact, hypermarkets don't stock up on commodities. Because of this kind of product turnover rate is high, that is, the store to store the goods to sell the cycle is very short. So, in an extreme case of panic buying, a supermarket warehouse of toilet paper goods is unable to meet the sudden surge in demand.

The shortage of manpower will also affect the speed of replenishment supermarkets. The original staffing of the stores is not enough to cope with today's rush. Staff have also been reduced by the outbreak, which has led to telecommuting and blockades in some parts of the country. In France, between 25 and 35 per cent of workers work from home because their schools are closed and they have to stay home with their children. French officials said they would consider a variety of measures to increase manpower.

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
Toilet paper has been sold out at a supermarket in London. Source: Interviewees

In the face of adversity, many European supermarket chains have started to take action.

On March 15th a group of big European supermarket chains, including TESCO, Sainsbury's and Asda, published a joint letter in several national newspapers saying they were working closely with governments and suppliers, to allow food to be moved quickly, and to be delivered more frequently to its stores, to make sure it was available on the shelves. The same goes for online shopping and self-service pick-ups.

They are also pleading with customers not to panic buy during the epidemic.

"But we also need your help. We have to hope that everyone understands each other. We understand your concerns, but sometimes buying more than you need can mean that others will get nothing. If we all work together, everyone can buy enough."

At the same time, a number of supermarkets have begun to impose restrictions on purchases. Aldi, a large german-based supermarket chain, has a limit of four items per person. In a long statement posted on Facebook on March 16, CEO Giles Hurley said he hopes the temporary restrictions will give more customers the opportunity to buy what they need every time they arrive.

In addition, he said he has increased orders to suppliers, the warehouse is also in full operation. "although staff have been restocking, the surge in demand has made it difficult to ensure there are no vacancies on the shelves. All of our stores restock several times a day, and even if you go today and see that it's not in stock, in most cases it will be in a few days."

Other retailers such as TESCO, Sainsbury's and Asda have made similar moves, limiting purchases of daily consumables such as vegetables, Pasta and toilet paper, in addition to sterilising hygiene products.

In order to reduce the risk of infection, some supermarkets began to implement time-division shopping. Take the REWE supermarket in Mulheiman der Ruhr, North rhine-westphalia, in Germany, which limits shopping between 6 and 9 a.m. to the "new crown high-risk Group" -- People over 60 and chronically ill, others can shop at 9-21 and don't shop together.

"The consumer is trying to gain control and the emergency purchase is essentially our attempt to control the situation. It's important to feel that we're at least doing something, that we're moving ahead, and that emergency buying is just that,"says Dimitrios Tsivrikos, a consumer and business psychologist at University College London.
